I get what you’re reaching for—and there is a real effect there—but the “hack the deeper brain and just slide into motion” picture is a bit too literal.

What’s actually going on (tight version)

* Stories and vivid imagery engage simulation networks (imagery, emotion, memory).
* They also lightly engage parts of the motor system—your brain rehearses actions (“motor imagery”).
* This can prime you: lower the effort to start, make a behavior feel more familiar, reduce hesitation.

But:

There isn’t a direct “same spot → just switch to movement” shortcut.

Movement still requires:

* motor cortex activation
* basal ganglia gating (go / no-go)
* coordination + context

So it’s not a bypass—it’s a bias.

